=========================================================
PURE VIRTUAL FUNCTIONS IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
A Pure Virtual Function is a virtual function that has no implementation
in the base class and is declared using '= 0'.

Syntax:

virtual ReturnType functionName(parameters) = 0;

Example:

virtual void draw() = 0;

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED PURE VIRTUAL FUNCTIONS?
=========================================================

Suppose every derived class MUST provide its own implementation of a
function.

Example:

Shape
 ├── Circle
 ├── Rectangle
 └── Triangle

Every shape should implement:

draw()

But there is no meaningful generic implementation of draw() in Shape.

Hence:

draw() should be Pure Virtual.

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Drawing Circle\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Shape* ptr = new Circle();

    ptr->draw();
}

Output:

Drawing Circle

=========================================================
WHAT DOES '= 0' MEAN?
=========================================================

'= 0' tells the compiler:

1. This function is Pure Virtual.
2. No implementation is required in this class.
3. Derived classes must implement it.
4. The class becomes an Abstract Class.

=========================================================
PURE VIRTUAL FUNCTION CREATES
=========================================================

Pure Virtual Function
         ↓
Abstract Class
         ↓
Cannot Create Objects
         ↓
Forces Derived Classes to Implement Function

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

Shape s;      // ERROR

Compilation Error:

Cannot instantiate abstract class.

=========================================================
MUST DERIVED CLASS OVERRIDE IT?
=========================================================

YES.

=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
};

int main()
{
    Circle c;     // ERROR
}

=========================================================

Reason:

Circle also becomes an Abstract Class because draw() was not overridden.

=========================================================
CORRECT VERSION
=========================================================

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Circle";
    }
};

=========================================================
CAN PURE VIRTUAL FUNCTIONS HAVE IMPLEMENTATION?
=========================================================

YES.

This is a very common interview question.

=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

void Shape::draw()
{
    cout << "Shape Draw\n";
}

=========================================================

Even though implementation exists:

Shape is STILL an Abstract Class.

=========================================================
CAN DERIVED CLASS CALL BASE IMPLEMENTATION?
=========================================================

YES.

=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

void Shape::draw()
{
    cout << "Base Draw\n";
}

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        Shape::draw();
        cout << "Circle Draw\n";
    }
};

Output:

Base Draw
Circle Draw

=========================================================
PURE VIRTUAL DESTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Another favorite interview question.

=========================================================

class Base
{
public:
    virtual ~Base() = 0;
};

Base::~Base()
{
}

=========================================================

Rule:

Pure Virtual Destructor MUST have a definition.

Reason:
Destructor is always called during object destruction.

=========================================================
INTERNAL WORKING
=========================================================

Pure Virtual Functions are also stored in:

vtable

Objects still contain:

vptr

Therefore:

Runtime Polymorphism still works.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Circle\n";
    }
};

Shape* ptr = new Circle();

ptr->draw();

Output:

Circle

=========================================================
USES OF PURE VIRTUAL FUNCTIONS
=========================================================

1. Achieve Abstraction
2. Create Abstract Classes
3. Define Interfaces
4. Force Derived Classes to Implement Behavior
5. Support Runtime Polymorphism
6. Enable Loose Coupling

=========================================================
REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Payment
{
public:
    virtual void pay() = 0;
};

class UPIPayment : public Payment
{
public:
    void pay() override
    {
        cout << "UPI Payment\n";
    }
};

class CreditCardPayment : public Payment
{
public:
    void pay() override
    {
        cout << "Credit Card Payment\n";
    }
};

Payment* p;

p = new UPIPayment();
p->pay();

p = new CreditCardPayment();
p->pay();

Same interface:

pay()

Different implementations.

=========================================================
PURE VIRTUAL FUNCTION vs VIRTUAL FUNCTION
=========================================================

Feature              Virtual        Pure Virtual
----------------------------------------------------------
Implementation       Usually Yes    Not Required
Syntax               virtual f()    virtual f() = 0
Instantiation        Allowed        Makes class abstract
Override Required    No             Yes
Purpose              Default Impl   Contract/Interface

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is a Pure Virtual Function?

Answer:
A virtual function declared using '=0' that makes the class abstract
and forces derived classes to implement the function.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Why do we use Pure Virtual Functions?

Answer:
To achieve abstraction and define mandatory behavior for derived
classes.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. What does '=0' mean?

Answer:
It tells the compiler that the function is Pure Virtual and the class
becomes abstract.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Can Pure Virtual Functions have implementation?

Answer:
YES.

Example:

virtual void draw() = 0;

void Shape::draw()
{
}

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Can we create objects of a class containing a Pure Virtual Function?

NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. If derived class doesn't override Pure Virtual Function?

Answer:
The derived class also becomes abstract.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Can Pure Virtual Functions participate in Runtime Polymorphism?

YES.

They are stored in vtable and use vptr.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. Can destructor be Pure Virtual?

YES.

But its definition is mandatory.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

A Pure Virtual Function is a virtual function declared using '=0'. It
has no mandatory implementation in the base class and forces derived
classes to provide their own implementation. A class containing at least
one pure virtual function becomes an Abstract Class and cannot be
instantiated. Pure virtual functions are widely used to achieve
abstraction and create interfaces in C++.

